3.  What is the core principle behind Tailwind CSS?
A.  "Utility-first" = Use small, specific classes to build your own designs from scratch.
    Instead of writing custom CSS styles for each element, you use small, reusable utility classes directly in your HTML (or JSX) to style your components.

    In Bootstrap, you'd use a class like btn btn-primary, which is a pre-styled component.
    In Tailwind, you'd build that button yourself using utility classes like:
    Ex - Without Tailwind-
         .btn {
              background-color: blue;
              color: white;
              padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
              border-radius: 0.25rem;
         }

         With Tailwind- 
         <button className="bg-blue-500 text-white px-4 py-2 rounded">
           Click Me
         </button>

    Use-Case- 
    ğŸ”¹Faster development â€” no switching between CSS and HTML/JSX.
    ğŸ”¹Consistent styling across the app.
    ğŸ”¹No naming hassle â€” you donâ€™t need to think of class names.
    ğŸ”¹Easier to maintain â€” everything is visible in one place.



4.  Whats the main difference between Bootstrap's "component-first" approach and Tailwind CSS's "utility-first" approach?
A.  Bootstrap: Component-first
    ğŸ”¹Classes are pre-styled components.
    ğŸ”¹You use a class like btn, and it comes with a whole set of styles baked in â€” padding, font, border, hover effect, etc.
    ğŸ”¹You don't build the design, you use what's given.
    Ex - <button class="btn btn-primary">
            Click Me
         </button>
    This button already has padding, colors, rounded corners, and hover styles â€” you didn't decide any of it.
    You can override it, but thatâ€™s not the main flow.

    Tailwind: Utility-first
    ğŸ”¹Classes are tiny, low-level building blocks that do one job only.
    ğŸ”¹You combine them to build your own design.
    ğŸ”¹There are no pre-styled buttons or cards â€” you create them how you want.
    Ex - <button class="bg-black text-white font-bold px-4 py-2 rounded">
            Click Me
         </button>
    You're fully in control of how the button looks â€” nothing is "pre-styled."

    ğŸ“ŒSo yes â€” both use classes, but Bootstrap gives you a cake, while Tailwind gives you the ingredients to bake your own.ğŸ°
















